[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Executive Summary[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1 [bold]Whether the UK’s implementation of CAP might put English farmers at a competitive disadvantage to their regional and European counterparts[bold].[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1 
[normal]A focus on short term competitive advantage
[normal]/disadvantage
[normal] 
[normal]masks the issu
[normal]e
[normal] of the long term
[normal] health of the environment and the extent to which th
[normal]is 
[normal]determines the viability and
[normal] future 
[normal]of farming, and thus the incomes that farmers derive from 
[normal]land management. 
[normal]We want to see the concept of environmental land management  ‘mainstreamed’, with
[normal] [bold]management of the environment no longer culturally divided into activities described as ‘farming’ and those attributed to 'conservation’. 
[normal]For example, 
[normal]wildflower grasslands perform 
[normal]important functions 
[normal]across the agricultural landscape. The insects they sup
[normal]port are crucial for the pollination of crops and this habitat provides food for all stages of their life cycle
[normal]. 
[normal] Invertebrates in wildflower grasslands play an important role in dung removal and soil creation. Wildflower meadows provide food and breeding 
[normal]areas for predator species such as beetles, spiders and parasitic wasps, which carry out natural pest control of insects in arable crops. Grassland soils are a major carbon sink and many wildflower species sustainably fix atmospheric nitrogen. These grassl
[normal]ands perform all of those functions AND provide 
[normal]high quality 
[normal]food which is produced with low inputs – an economic and environmental benefit. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2 
[normal]The 
[normal]way in which CAP is implemen
[normal]ted must help farmers build ecological 
[normal]resilience and restore the environmen
[normal]tal performance of the land – ensuring that it continues to provide food
[normal], but also that it delivers 
[normal]environmental public goods other than food. If farmers are adequately rewarded for the delivery 
[normal]of environmental public goods 
[normal]then this should help 
[normal]ensure t
[normal]hat 
[normal]they 
[normal]are not placed at com
[normal]petitive 
[normal]disadvantage in the future.
[normal] Indeed it will ensure that th
[normal]ose farmers who 
[normal]currently 
[normal]do most to protect 
[normal]environmental public goods 
[normal]will 
[normal]not be disadvantaged. A
[normal] research project 
[normal]that 
[normal]forms part of the UK National 
[normal]Ecosystem Assessment has concluded
[normal] that spending CAP funds on improving access to attractive countryside, protecting wildlife and cutting greenhouse gases could produce annual benefits of over £18bn, for a loss of less than £0.5bn in UK agricultural produc
[normal]tion.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal] 
[normal]An approach that takes account of the full range of goods and services farmers can provide, 
[normal]require
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]effective
[normal] 
[normal]Pillar I G
[normal]reening measures 
[normal]and a well funded Rural Development P
[normal]ro
[normal]gramme that prioritises environmental land
[normal] management schemes
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal] Embedding a value for 
[normal]environmental 
[normal]public goods
[normal] [bold]in farm management via greening measures linked to direct payments, provides a justification for public money to be given to farmers. It provides to society and businesses a clear message about the important role that farmers play in protecting and enhanci
[normal]ng the ecosystems that provide us with these goods and services.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5
[normal] It is 
[normal]also 
[normal]in the long term interest of the farming industry to have healthy soils, areas that support pollinating insects and predatory insects, and so on. The value of having nature
[normal] side by side with farming are clear and in the longer term we believe can bring competitive advantage.  
