[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.8
[normal] 
[normal]New Environmental Land Management Schemes[bold] 
[normal]Agri environment schemes 
[normal]are a 
[normal]key mechanism for Government delivery of policy objectives
[normal]. 
[normal]The added value that 
[normal]they can bring 
[normal]for society, the economy 
[normal]and rural communities is under
[normal]-
[normal]appreciated. We refer the committee to a series of ‘Farming for A Living Landscape’ case studies which we have produced
[normal] 
[normal]http://www.wildlifetrusts.org/living-
[normal]landscape/farming
[normal]. 
[normal]T
[normal]hese show how farmers’ entry into agri environment schemes, when supported by e
[normal]ffective advice, 
[normal]can bring wider benefits. 
[normal]For example, 
[normal]Avon Wildlife Trust 
[normal]h
[normal]elp
[normal]s farmers 
[normal]to get into Higher Level Ste
[normal]wardship 
[normal]schemes, enabling 
[normal]them to 
[normal]m
[normal]anage their fields with low inputs.  The lower input costs provide an economic benefit to the landowner as well as a positive benefit for ecosystem services. Combining gains for wildlife with potential commercial benefits for landowners is a high priority 
[normal]for this 
[normal]project
[normal]. 
[normal]More generally, work undertaken by the Countryside and Community Research Institute (2010) has shown that 
[normal]every £1 of Environmental Stewardship money generates a total output in the local economy of £1.42.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.
[normal]9
[normal] 
[normal]As mentioned above, 
[normal]appropriate advice and facilitation (which can for example bring farmers together to develop collaborative agreements across wider areas) 
[normal]is a key element in successful land management schemes. We welcome current discussions around the 
[normal]merits of a ‘facilit
[normal]ation fund’, 
[normal]which would ensure that farmers would have access to appropriate advice and help
[normal],
[normal] and that the opportunities for added value were fully realised. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1
[normal]0
[normal] The movement of 15% monies  from Pillar I to Pillar II can  ensure that maximum benefit is  derived from measures across the whole rural development programme
[normal]. The
[normal] strategic 
[normal]and SMART 
[normal]application  of 
[normal]all 
[normal]measures 
[normal]within Pillar II when 
[normal] 
[normal]e
[normal]mployed
[normal]  according
[normal]ly (including NELMS)
[normal] 
[normal] can if 
[normal] effected 
[normal]properly secure the progress of RDP in delivering its objectives for farm competition across the EU.
