[normal]2. The [bold]steps the Government might take in implementing CAP to help tenant farmers in upland areas, and to take acc[bold]ount of issues pertaining to common land.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1 
[normal]F
[normal]inancial support for 
[normal]tenant farmers in upland areas should better reflect the scale of the ecosystem service benefits and the quality of the benefits upland farming can provide
[normal]. The new CAP should be used to support farmers and tenant farmers who protect and enhance the value of upland catchments in 
[normal]retaining and slowing down water flow to reduce flooding impacts, providing clean drinking water, storing and sequestering carbon a
[normal]nd providing special habitats for declining species. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2 
[normal]Farmers in these areas can derive bene
[normal]fits from 
[normal]recrea
[normal]tion and tourism or potentially cou
[normal]l
[normal]d be paid directly by businesses such as water companies. But there is currently not a clear model 
[normal]or mecha
[normal]nism 
[normal]for 
[normal]the 
[normal]provision of income to farmers for ecosystem services other than food
[normal], especially in the more marginal farming systems. We must therefore 
[normal]look to the direct payments system
[normal], including via the Greening payment,
[normal] and 
[normal]to the 
[normal]New Environmental Land
[normal] Management Schemes 
[normal]of Pillar II 
[normal]to 
[normal]provide support 
[normal]for those marginal but environmentally valuable farms and farming systems –in upland areas and elsewhere. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3 The value of extensive grazing systems, where the level of grazing animals provides protecti
[normal]on for important ecosystem services, but where income from livestock is relatively poor, must be r
[normal]ecognised, with support provided
[normal] for these farmers to market and sell what are often high quality products. We think tha
[normal]t much can be learnt f
[normal]r
[normal]o
[normal]m 
[normal]existing 
[normal]goo
[normal]d practice
[normal]. 
[normal]For example 
[normal]in Worcestershire
[normal], The Wildlife Trust has teamed up with Old Yarr Estates, promoting the sale of beef from cattle that have been grazing on the Trust’s nature reserves. 
[normal]http://www.worcswildlifetrust.co.uk/wildlife-friendly-beef-boxes
[normal].
