[normal]3. The [bold]steps Government need[bold]s[bold] to take to ensure the reformed CAP will be less bureaucratic than its predecessor and what might prevent this ambition from being achieved[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1 
[normal]While it is recognised there are key principles such as simplicity of design and a desire not to ‘gold plate’
[normal] 
[normal]schemes, these should not constrain thinking on how to achieve potential gains.  Simple delivery should not mean partial delivery and effecti
[normal]ve environmental benefits need not amount to “gold 
[normal]plating”.
[normal] The
[normal] key principle should be focused around SMART design identifying where and how a number effective environmental outcomes can be deli
[normal]vered in combination with 
[normal]agricultural outcomes.
[normal] There should be no confusion between simplicity of design and ineffective delivery.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2 We believe that the importance of appropriate advice and facilitation is key to reducing time spent on paperwork and that a flexible and nuanced approach is needed t
[normal]o both this and inspection regimes. The delivery of Greening through a 
[normal]National Certification Scheme (NCS) 
[normal]wo
[normal]uld certainly provide a clearer
[normal] and more straightforward process, and a single but tiered Environmental Land Management Scheme should introduce som
[normal]e further simplicity. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4. [bold]How the Government [bold]might [bold]define the minimum activity required for qual[bold]ification as an ‘active farmer’[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1 
[normal]As mentioned above
[normal],
[normal] low stocking densities are vital for maintaining and enhancing the health of many ecosystem services, 
[normal]for example grassland systems that can slow down or store water, such as the culm grasslands of Devon or the maintenance of upland or lowland heath vegetation. It is vital that the minimum activity required does not penalise those 
[normal]low intensity 
[normal]management 
[normal]systems and inadvertently lead to damage to habitats that are the source of farm incomes in themselves for example through tourism incomes.   
[normal]The level of minimum activity should
[normal] th
[normal]er
[normal]e
[normal]fore  be able to refl
[normal]ect the
[normal] 
[normal]farming system that is 
[normal]app
[normal]ropriate 
[normal] 
[normal]to maintaining  such 
[normal] habitats
[normal] and other services provided by them
[normal]. A
[normal] ‘one size fits 
[normal]all’ method
[normal] of
[normal] defining appropriate levels  of minimum activity 
[normal]should 
[normal]thus be avoided
[normal]. If implemented 
[normal]properly 
[normal]‘minimum activity’ could 
[normal] confer its own sense of value to 
[normal]those habitats, farming  systems and other services provided by such activity.
