[normal]5 How [bold]Government [bold]can [bold]ensure that CAP delivers the best environmental benefits while supporting food production[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1 
[normal]We believe that 
[normal]CAP payments 
[normal]should 
[normal]address areas where there are 
[normal]currently 
[normal]market failures – specifically,
[normal] provide farmers with payments for the ecosystem goods and services they provide to the public
[normal]. 
[normal]We are very concerned that marginal farm systems that provide society with 
[normal]high quality 
[normal]p
[normal]ublic goods will remain on the verge of, or will be tipped into, bankruptcy, whilst 
[normal]some 
[normal]farming systems that continue to damage the natural environment will 
[normal]continue to 
[normal]be rewarded with public money
[normal].   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2 
[normal]I
[normal]t is essential that the public perceive the ou
[normal]tcomes from the money they provide to farmers. 
[normal]T
[normal]here must be a transparent way of the public seeing that the payments they make to farmers both via Pillar I and Pillar II deliver outcomes 
[normal]in addition to food
[normal].  The 
[normal]30% 
[normal]Greening payment of approximately £495
[normal] million per year to English farmers, must be made to work effectively to deliver perceptible environmental benefit. It should also be clear to the public that the bulk of the direct payment money (70%) should not be linked to damaging activities, with a r
[normal]obustly enforced cross compliance system. 
